[üì∏: @lucymountain] Things that you deserve to feel guilty for: - actual, genuine crimes. Like murder. Or not liking Lizzo.

Things that you never deserve to feel guilty for: - eating food
- enjoying food
- having a full stomach

Guilt does not belong on your plate. Eating is not a crime. And shame doesn't lead anywhere positive or healthy, ever. "The last decade has given us more body positive triumphs than ever before, with diet culture seemingly always ready to come back swinging in each round. One year detox teas reign supreme, the next we receive Lizzo as our queen. Some days, it really does feel like we‚Äôre locked in the final superhero battle ‚Äì body liberation on one side, body shame the other ‚Äì and I‚Äôm not sure which way it‚Äôs going to go yet... Since the bulk of body conversation in recent years has happened online, I‚Äôve had a front row seat. I‚Äôve watched countless people wake up to the fact that diets don‚Äôt work. I‚Äôve seen fatphobia being discussed on stages bigger than the original fat activists of the 1960s would‚Äôve believed. I‚Äôve witnessed brands start to represent a more diverse range of bodies than ever before ‚Äì or risk the wrath of the internet.

I‚Äôve also heard first-hand how our body struggles are morphing into new, equally unattainable shapes. Social media ‚Äì for all its positive parts ‚Äì has raised the stakes of bodily perfection to new levels. Between filters and Photoshop and an endless influx of Instagram models, we really are more appearance-focused than ever. In 2010, some 59,372 people had buttock augmentation procedures worldwide, by 2017 that number had soared to 372,496. So while the standard of beauty we‚Äôre being sold is different, is it any less damaging?" - me for @graziauk üíÉüèΩ full article in my bio if you feel like a read! üíúüíôüíöüåàüåû ‚Ä¢ [Image description: an screenshot of an article written by Megan that reads "How we refused to keep shrinking during the 2010s: Rejecting traditional narrow definitions of beauty went hand in hand with freeing our minds, says Megan Crabbe"] #bodypositivity #bodyacceptance #bodyimage #beautystandards #allbodiesaregoodbodies

A study was released earlier this week arguing that including exercise requirement labeling on food would be beneficial for people's health. So on the packaging for everything you eat would also be how many minutes of physical activity you'd need to do to burn the calories off. Because why not just tip a few more people into lifelong disordered relationships with food & movement!

The thing is, if you've ever experienced an eating disorder, you probably don't need those labels. Because you probably already know those numbers. If you're like me you probably memorised them by heart and lived by them so relentlessly that you'll never be able to forget them. And you'll also know that existing in that mindset is something we should be protecting people from at all costs, not pushing them towards.

Honestly? Not only is this idea wildly scientifically inaccurate (different people have different energy needs & absorb/expend nutrients differently, duh), it's also ableist (not everyone can hop up for a run after every snack), and it also straight up doesn't make sense. If we 'burned off' everything we ate, we'd all be dead. Our bodies NEED calories to function, even if all we're doing is staying in bed.

I'm so sick of food & nutrition advice that's rooted in fatphobia, bad science and a complete disregard for the fact that mental health IS HEALTH TOO. Can we please leave this shit in 2019? Thank you. Now please excuse me whilst I eat my dinner and move precisely nowhere. üíúüíôüíöüåàüåû

üéÑ Today I want to hold a little space for the people who aren't feeling merry or joyful & might be wondering how they're gonna get through the holiday season.

The people who lost someone this year and are bracing themselves for the first time without them.

The people who are going home to guaranteed body shaming & fatphobia.

The people whose mental health issues won't magically disappear just because it's Christmas.

The people with eating disorders who are worried about holding onto recovery when everything is so food-centred this time of year.

The people who are struggling to afford every day life and might go into debt trying to keep up with the celebrations.

The queer kids who aren't able to fully be themselves around family because it might not be safe.

The people gathering strength to fight against racist comments round the dinner table.

The people who don't drink anymore and will have to keep explaining why because who doesn't drink over the holidays?

The carers, the retail workers, the hospital staff, everyone working extra time under extra pressure for not enough extra pay.

Anyone who's just feeling overwhelmed and like they can't keep up with it all.

I see you. And I want you to know that it's totally okay to feel exactly how you feel. To get through this year however you can. To protect and preserve yourself whenever you're able to. And to take this season a day at a time. üíúüíôüíöüåàüåû ‚Ä¢ [Image description: a blue and white billboard for @scarcurtis book It's Not Okay to Feel Blue that reads "it's okay if it's not the most wonderful time of the year" against a cloudy sky] #mentalhealthawareness #anxietyrelief #edrecovery #selfcare #holidayseason

What I'm wearing to the polling station tomorrow to #VoteTactically #VoteLabour and #GetBorisOut üíÉüèΩ‚ú® I do not believe that there is a party in this election without flaws. I do not believe that every manifesto promise is a guarantee or that every issue in this country will be fixed with a vote.

But I do believe that this election comes down to our core moral values as human beings and what kind of people we want to be. Do we want to be the kind who take care of our elderly and disabled communities? The kind who value education and invest in the life-saving services that every one of us has, does or will one day need? The kind who realise that people who come from unfamiliar places and might not look or speak like us are also people who deserve respect and safety? The kind who see the value that LGBTQIA+ people bring to society? The kind who don't believe that people are worth more just because they earn more? The kind who believe that all people - children and adults alike - deserve at the very least, food, shelter and healthcare?

I do not believe that there is a party in this election without flaws. But I do believe that the party who've been in power for 9 years already have shown us exactly what kind of people they are. And they are not the kind of people I trust to do better. Please use your vote tomorrow, if not for yourself, for someone in a more vulnerable position whose life could quite literally depend on it. üíúüíôüíöüåàüåû ‚Ä¢ [Image description: Megan is standing outside a building with a gold roof wearing a gold satin minidress and gold knee high wedges with a heel chunky enough stomp the UK's current Tory government]

üì∏: @alex_cameron üå∏ Today was the first day in a lot of years that I found myself scrolling through the posts of an impossibly beautiful model and wishing I knew how it felt to look like that.

I wondered how the people she dates treat her - is she constantly worshipped? Does she still get screwed over? How easy must it be to find someone else when it doesn't work out? Would the person I'm dating like her better?

I wondered how it feels existing online with so many likes pouring in on every outfit post. How every shot could be a front cover. How it feels to be the ideal.

I wondered how clothes feel when they fit like that and whether she was really having as good of a time in that club as it seems. How much of that joy comes from moving through the world in a way that looks completely flawless.

I've never seen someone who is SO exactly the way I dreamed of looking for nearly my entire life. And it shook me. So now I'm catching myself.

Because I know that this person probably deals with the same shit in their dating life as the rest of us do - beauty is not a guarantee for respect or connection or understanding.

Because I know that there is space on the internet for both of us, and that looking like the ideal was never the point of what I'm doing here. It isn't why any of you are here either, and I am so so grateful you are here.

Because she maybe still changed her outfit 8 times and felt insecure and retook the picture over & over and didn't have that good of a time. Because I know nothing about her and her life other than the fact that she's up against the same suffocating standards of beauty that I am, and she's surviving the best she can too.

I will never know how it feels to look like her. And that's okay. I know how it feels to look like me. Every tear it took in recovery. Every moment of freedom that body acceptance gave me. Every effort to build this level of peace and every privilege that still made the building easier. Every bite, every breath, every bit of sunlight this body has allowed me to feel.

I know how it feels to look like me, and I know now that I was never supposed to be anyone else. I hope she feels peaceful in her body, too. üíú

üé®: @crazyheadcomics üåª There's a tweet going round that says "I wonder what would happen if everyone who goes to therapy spent that time helping other people instead". So lemme just clear some things up. Going to therapy is NOT: - Selfish
- Self-indulgent
- A waste of time
- Shameful
- Always accessible (but it should be)
- Embarrassing
- Something to feel guilty about
- Stopping people from helping others

Taking steps to manage your mental health so that you can function to the best of your ability & show up in the world more fully? ESPECIALLY with ongoing mental health stigma perpetuated by bullshit like this? That is courageous. That is strong. That is choosing to heal in ways that will make you better able to help others in the long run. So thank you.

Fuck therapy shame, fuck medication shame, fuck all the kinds of shame we're conditioned to carry simply for being human beings. You're allowed to heal yourself first, in fact the world would probably be a much healthier place if more people did. üíúüíôüíöüåàüåû ‚Ä¢ [Image description: an illustration by @crazyheadcomics showing a person wearing a blue dress and holding a watering can over their head. There are flowers growing from them and writing by their side which reads "going to therapy is nothing to be ashamed of,  you are actively working on being a healthier, happier person - that's something commendable! Trying to heal is not weak"] #therapy #therapyiscool #therapyquotes #anxietyrelief #anxietyhelp #depressionhelp #mentalhealthquotes #mentalhealthawareness

"Pandaface came about a few years ago when I first started taking what I do off the internet. My biggest anxiety around that, and around meeting people who followed me, was always whether I was going to be the version of me that these people think I am - am I going to live up to their expectation of me? Especially in those early years, everything I put up on the internet was so intensely positive, like so sickeningly rainbow happiness and joy. I would not write an honest post about my mental health, it would all have to be uplifting happiness, so I had to be that in real life as well - and I am not that. I am actually, at times, a deeply sad and negative person, as most people are sometimes.

The effect of having to try and live up to these expectations after the events left me utterly exhausted. I was so drained because I'd been putting on this persona of the Panda, so we started calling it Pandaface. I think over the years I started realising that I couldn't keep doing that at my expense - it made me tired and it was also just so deeply rooted in this fear of people not liking me. I thought I had to be the most positive version of myself in order to be likeable... So I just started allowing myself to take that mask off a bit, and start being more fully human." - me for @theunedit Volume 1 Digital Issue ‚ú® you can find the whole interview through the link in my bio if you wanna! üíúüíôüíöüåàüåû ‚Ä¢ [Image description: a photo by @larabellenewyork of Megan is standing in a New York street with traffic behind her, she's wearing a black and white dogstooth patterned jumper with a black beret and looking very intensely into the camera] #TheUneditGoesDigital #TheUnedit #influencer #influencerlife

I'm gonna say this one loud and clear: Your body doesn't deserve to be punished because eating is not a crime.

Even if you ate past the point of comfort. Regardless of what size your body is. Eating. Is. Not. A. Crime. And treating your body like it is by restricting or compulsively trying to "work off" the calories you consumed is more likely to throw you into a diet/binge cycle than help you find balance.

There's nothing wrong with wanting to prioritise getting some more nutrients after a not-so-nutritious phase of eating, but that doesn't have to mean making food choices from a place of guilt, shame or body hatred. Having a healthy relationship with food (one that isn't built on obsession or punishment) is just as important as the nutrients. Because mental health is health too.

If you're struggling today and you're not sure how to deal with the food guilt, please please consider looking into intuitive eating before starting a crash diet or "cleanse" (spoiler alert: those don't work). Check out Health at Every Size by Linda Bacon ü•Ø Intuitive Eating by Evelyn Tribole & Elyse Resch ü•ß Just Eat It by Laura Thomas üçâ  follow people here like @laurathomasphd @encouragingdietitian
@chr1styharrison @dietitiananna üçï

üé®: @thefemalewarhol üåø Ways that I let people treat me when I didn't believe I was worth any more:

Like I was just a body.

Like my time didn't have value.

Like my emotional labour wasn't labour.

Like my voice mattered less than theirs.

Like I didn't deserve to be compensated for my work.

Like my feelings were too much.

Like my mental health made me a burden.

Like I was clueless when I wasn't.

Like I was a shitty person when I wasn't.

Like they had more right to define me than I did.

Like I had endless capacity to take care of everyone before myself.

Like my ideas were worthless.

Like I was hard to love.

Ways that I'm no longer letting people treat me because I know that I'm worth more:

All of the above. And I forgive myself for not seeing that worth sooner. üíúüíôüíöüåàüåû [Image description: an illustration by @thefemalewarhol showing a white brick wall with grass growing underneath it, on the wall are the words "forgive yourself for all the shit you let slide"] #selfworth #selfkindness #growthmindset #knowyourworth

üé®: @bodypositive_mom üå∏ There are very few things that piss me off more than the idea that after someone grows & gives birth to an ENTIRE HUMAN BEING, their main priority should be shrinking themselves back down to a body that shows no sign of it. As if every mark, scar, and extra space created to house a whole person is anything short of magical and worthy of worship.

Pay close attention to the ways that diet culture preys on people when they're at their most vulnerable - after the emotional upheaval of giving birth, before major life moments like getting married, straight after puberty when our bodies are first changing along with everything else in our worlds. The incentive for making us latch onto the need to change our bodies in these times is simple: it makes a fuck tonne of money. The post-baby and pre-wedding diet industries are worth billions. But our mental well-being should be worth more.

You are NEVER required to "get your body back" after any life event or change (spoiler alert: bodies are supposed to change over time). And the idea that making yourself smaller should be your main focus when your body has done just about the most miraculous thing it could do, is bullshit. Your body never went anywhere. It just became the version it needed to become to sustain life, and that's fucking beautiful. üíúüíôüíöüåàüåû ‚Ä¢ [Image description: an illustration by @bodypositive_mum that shows different painted foods with a title above them that reads "Foods to get your body back after baby". Below each food are the words "you never lost your body after baby! It's ok and normal that your body changed. You don't need a smaller body to be worthy!"] #bodypositive #postpartum #postpartumbody #bodyacceptance #bodyafterbaby #postbabybody  #fuckdietculture
